## Closing a task — `mc finish` is mandatory

`mc finish` posts the reflection and sets the status atomically. A bare
`mc done`/`mc review` without a prior reflection comment is rejected by the
backend with 400 — `mc finish` is the only way to make reflection + status
change atomic:

```bash
mc finish [--review] "$(cat <<'EOF'
{% for f in reflection_required_fields %}## {{ f }}
[...]

{% endfor %}EOF
)"
```

`--review` flag = a reviewer checks it (code/API/security); without
`--review` = straight to `done` (housekeeping/research/docs).

**{{ reflection_required_fields|length }} required fields** (single source of
truth: `backend/app/constants.py`):
{% for f in reflection_required_fields %}{{ loop.index }}. **{{ f }}**
{% endfor %}
At least {{ reflection_min_chars }} characters. The backend blocks the status
transition if the reflection is missing or too short. The last field
(`{{ reflection_required_fields[-1] }}`) is automatically saved to memory as
an agent lesson.

## Review vs. done — deciding for yourself

Since ADR-023, you decide whether a task goes through `review` or straight to
`done`. A reviewer is opt-in, not a mandatory gate.

**Send to review when:**
- A code change is being pushed to `main`
- New public API, endpoint, or schema change
- Security-relevant change (auth, secrets, input validation)
- You're unsure the solution is correct

**Go straight to `done` when:**
- Pure housekeeping (renaming, docs, dependency update with no logic)
- Small, reversible fix with no side effects
- Research/analysis task (no code, just findings → deliverable)

Rule of thumb: when in doubt, review — bothering a reviewer costs little, a
broken `main` costs a lot.

## Checklist — mandatory before the first work step

Create a checklist as the very first thing via `mc checklist add "..."` per
step. Mark each completed step done only when the work is physically
complete and you've verified the result yourself — never "will probably
work". Use `mc checklist skip <id> --reason "..."` for out-of-role items.

## Progress & recovery

Post a short progress comment after every important step:
`mc comment progress "<Update — Evidence — Next>"` — this gives a successor
the current state immediately after a session reset/crash. Use `mc recover`
after a container restart to fetch the current task prompt plus a fresh
dispatch_attempt_id.
